@Poketuber Supreme No, std::endl isn't needed in that case. To end the line, you should be using the newline character, \n. If you need to end the line *and* flush the stream, that's what std::endl is for. It's the equivalent of doing

    stream << '\n' << std::flush;

So if you don't need to flush the stream, there's no point in wasting performance by performing an unnecessary flush.

Wdym? Return isn't a function, it's a keyword. You use it to exit a function.

e.g.

    void print(int a) noexcept
    {
        if (a < 0)
            return;

        std::cout << a << '\n';
    }

If it's a non-void function, it should also return data that matches the function's return type.

    // Return type is int.
    inline int add(int a, int b) no except
    {
        // Returns sum of a and b. 
        return a + b;
    }

Another example:

    // Returns type is bool.
    bool print(int a) noexcept
    {
        if (a < 0)
            return false;

        std::cout << a << '\n';
        return true;
    }

