If you’re referring to std::array, it’s an STL (standard template library) container. In C++, you should never really be using raw arrays (C-style arrays, e.g. int arr[]) unless you’re implementing your own data structure, or something like that. Instead, you should be using STL containers ( https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/container ). The first one you should always consider is std::vector. std::vector is a container which stores elements contiguously, similar to raw arrays, and elements can be added and removed from it at any time.

e.g.

    // Creates a vector with three elements
    std::vector<int> vec{1, 2, 3};
    // Adds 4 to the back of the vector.
    vec.emplace_back(4);
    // Removes element “2”, by passing an iterator which points to that element to the erase member function.
    vec.erase(vec.begin() + 1);

If the size of your array isn’t going to change, and the size is known at compile-time, you should use std::array. std::array allocates its memory on the stack, and it’s pretty much just a safer wrapper for raw stack arrays.

e.g.

    std::array<int, 3> arr{1, 2, 3};
    for (int num : arr)
        std::cout << num << ‘\n’;

However, since it allocates the memory on the stack, it may not be ideal if you’re going to be storing a very massive amount of elements. In that case, you should use std::vector. If you’re not going to add those elements immediately, you can pre-allocate the memory you’ll eventually need using std::vector<T>::reserve or std::vector<T>::resize.

Return just exits a function early.

e.g.

    // Will only print the value of a if it isn’t negative.
    void f(int a) noexcept
    {
        if (a < 0)
            return;
        std::cout << a << ‘\n’;
    }

If the return type of the function isn’t void, it must also return some data that matches the return type.

e.g.

    // Returns a float.
     inline float add(float a, float b) noexcept
    {
        return a + b;
    }

