The main issues are that you’re missing a << before std::endl in your first std::cout statement, and in your last std::cout statement, you have a << at the end but nothing after it. You’re also using std::string, but you never included the header file that contains its declaration, so you need to include <string>.

But there’s also a bunch of other things that you should change:

- Don’t do using namespace std, it’s bad practice. Since everything in the standard library is defined within the std namespace, you need to prefix all standard library symbols with std::.

e.g.

    std::cout << “Hello, world!\n”;

- Since you are only viewing the contents of the string, and not using any features that std::string provides, you should just use std::string_view from <string_view> instead. std::string_view was added in C++17, so make sure you set your C++ standard to that. Compared to std::string, there’s not much you can do with it; as it’s name implies, it’s just used to view the contents of a string. The nice thing about it is that it doesn’t allocate the memory for the string, so it is a bit faster than std::string. This also means that the string must actually exist while you’re viewing it, so make sure that the string data never gets freed while you still need it (not that this can happen in your code, just thought you should know this).

- If a variable isn’t going to change, and it can be evaluated at compile-time, make it constexpr. Otherwise, make it const.

- Almost always use uniform initialization, with { }, instead of copy initialization, with =, or the old-school direct initialization, with ( ), as uniform initialization is much safer and avoid the most vexing parse. 

 e.g.

    int i{8};
    int *ptr{&i};
    std::string_view str{“Hello, World”};
    std::string_view &ref{str};

When you initialize a fundamental type with { }, it does not allow implicit narrowing conversions. For example, this means that you can initialize a double by passing it a float, but you can’t initialize a float by passing it a double, since a double is twice the size of a float, so a float can’t hold its value. If for some reason you still want to pass the value of a larger type to a smaller type, you’ll have to explicitly cast it, using static_cast, although you may lose some data.

e.g.

    float f1{64.0};
    double d1{f1}; // Ok.

    double d2{80.0};
    float f2{d2}; // Error, implicit narrowing not allowed.
    float f3{static_cast<float>(d2)}; // Ok, but preferably should be avoided.

As previously mentioned, uniform initialization also avoids the most vexing parse. For instance, consider the following line of code:

    Foo foo(Foo());

A novice may assume that that line is declaring an object of type Foo by copying a temporary Foo object into its constructor. In actuality, that line is a function declaration named foo, which returns a copy of Foo and takes in an unnamed parameter of type Foo by value. This is how all C++ compilers are required to interpret it. However, take a look at this line:

    Foo foo{Foo{}};

This line actually defines a variable of type Foo. Another nice thing about uniform initialization is that it doesn’t require you to specify the type all the time. For example,

    struct Point final
    {
        int x, y;
    };

    inline Point getLocation() noexcept
    {
        return {8, 5}; // equivalent to Point(8, 5) or Point{8, 5}.
    }

The only reason you may want to not use uniform initialization that I can think of is when you want to avoid calling a constructor that takes in an std::initializer_list object, as uniform initialization will always prefer those constructors. If you don’t know what std::initializer_list is (not to be confused with constructor initializer lists, which are a completely different thing, but unfortunately have a very similar name), it is used to pass multiple values of the same type into an object. It is typically used with container types, like std::array and std::vector. You can create an initializer_list using curly braces, similarly to how you would initialize raw arrays.

e.g.

    std::vector<int> vec{1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

That line is equivalent to

    std::vector<int> vec = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

or

    std::vector<int> vec({1, 2, 3, 4, 5});

or even

    std::vector<int> vec{std::initializer_list{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}};

std::vector has a constructor that takes in a size_type n variable, which allocated enough memory for n amount of elements, and a constructor that takes in an std::initializer list. Since uniform initialization will always call a constructor that takes in an std::initializer_list, if one exists, this line:

    std::vector<int> vec{5};

will create a vector with one element in it, an int with the value of five. If your intention was to allocate enough memory for five elements, you’ll have to use the old style of initialization:

    std::vector<int> vec(5);

For this reason, container types are usually always initialized with ( ) unless you want to call the constructor that takes in an std::initializer_list.

-If you need to flush the stream and end the line, use std::endl. If you just need to end the line, use ‘\n’. Otherwise, you’re wasting performance by flushing the stream, and it makes your intention less clear.

