@mardicai Lol no, that’s not how you do it. A namespace provides a named scope for your symbols.

e.g.

    namespace foo
    {
        void func() noexcept
        {
            std::cout << “Hello\n”;
        }
    }

    namespace bar
    {
        void func() noexcept
        {
            std::cout << “World\n”;
        }
    }

    int main()
    {
        foo::func(); // Prints “Hello”.
        bar::func(); // Prints “World”.
        func(); // Error, no global function “func” exists.

        return 0;
    }

Everything in the standard library is defined inside the std namespace. As such, all symbols that you use from the standard library must be prefixed with std::. This does *not* mean you have to also prefix the core language components with it. So the correct way to write that program would be:

    int main()
    {
        std::cout << “Hello world\n”;
        return 0;
    }

The using namespace declaration makes it so that the compiler treats all symbols defined in the given namespace as if they were defined in the global namespace. This can result in a multitude of issues, like name collisions, which is when you have two or more symbols with the same name, and the compiler is not sure which one it should use, or the linker isn’t sure which one to link, etc. By prefixing every symbol with their namespace name, it also makes it clear where everything is from.

