@Meow The right way is to not do using namespace std. Since every symbol in the standard library is defined inside the std namespace, you need prefix the symbol names with std::.

e.g.

    #include <iostream>
    #include <string_view>

    int main()
    {
        std::string_view name;
        std::cout << “What’s your name?\n”;
        std::getline(std::cin, name);
        std::cout << “Hello, “ << name << ‘\n’;

        return 0;
    }

The problem with the using namespace declaration is that it exposes all the contents of the namespace into the global namespace, and this could result in a multitude of problems, like name collisions. It also makes it unclear what library the symbols you’re using are from. Using namespace should only really be used if you’re using something from a namespace with a long name, like std::chrono, and you’re in a limited scope, such as a function. Even then, it’s better to just expose the symbols you’re actually using, with the using declaration.

e.g.

    // Only exposes system_clock into the global namespace. 
    using std::chrono::system_clock;
   const system_clock::time_point now{system_clock::now()};

@RealKasi Yes, that’s exactly how it is supposed to behave. As I previously said, the overloaded >> operator just gets one word, and std::getline gets the entire line. The nice thing about >> is that it can be used to get input of any fundamental type, such as int, float, long, short, etc. std::getline, on the other hand, only gets the input as a string.

If you want to get one word and ignore the other, you can use std::cin.ignore().

e.g.

    // Gets the first word of each line, disregarding the rest.
    std::string_view input1, input2;
    std::cin >> input1; 
    std::cin.ignore(std::numeric_limits<std::streamsize>::max(), ‘\n’);
    std::cin >> input2;

The ignore functions takes in an std::streamsize n, which is 1 by default, and an int delim, which is EOF by default. “n” is how many characters it should ignore. “delim” is delimiting character. When this character is found, it’ll stop ignoring input. To make it ignore all input until a newline character is found, you pass std::numeric_limits<std::streamsize>::max() for “n”, and ‘\n’ for “delim.” 

But if you just want to get the entire line, that’s what std::getline is for.

What do you mean sometimes things get worse? I presume you’re talking about the overloaded >> operator, as std::cin is just a console input stream, that can be used with the >> operator or std::getline. You use >> to read a single word.

For example,

    // Prints each word on a new line
    std::string_view word;
    while (std::cin >> word)
        std::cout << word << ‘\n’;

std::getline, on the other hand, will read the entire line. You should use whichever suits your needs.

