Pointers can be used for a lot of things. Here’s some examples:

- Dynamic memory allocation. When you allocate memory using new, you get a pointer to the memory you just allocated. You shouldn’t really be using new or owning memory using raw pointers, unless you have a good reason to. Instead, use a smart pointer, like std::unique_ptr, for the added safety net.

E.g.

    std::unique_ptr<int> num{std::make_unique<int>(25)};
    std::cout << *num << ‘\n’;

- Polymorphic objects. You can create a base class and have multiple classes inherit from it. Then, you can create a pointer to the base class and give it a memory address of any of the sub classes.

E.g.

    // Same pointer types, pointing to different class types. 
    std::unique_ptr<Base> base1{std::make_unique<Sub1>()};
    std::unique_ptr<Base> base2{std::make_unique<Sub2>()};

- Pointers are reassignable, while references are not. This means that references must be given a value immediately upon creation, and you cannot have them reference a different variable. Because pointers are just integers storing a memory address, you can assign a different memory address to them at any time. You can even just assign nullptr to them, then give them a real value later.

E.g.

    int a{64};
    int b{32};

    int &ref{a};
    int *ptr{&a};

    ref = b; // Assigns a to b, ref still references a.
    ptr = &b; // Ptr now points to b, the value of “a” remains unchanged.

- You also might be using pointers a lot if you’re working with a C library, as references don’t exist in C, so you’ll end up using pointers for things you would typically use a reference for.

Here are some more less common uses of pointers that you might find in legacy code:

- Optional function parameters. You can have a function take in a pointer, and have it check whether it’s nullptr or not. If it is, ignore it, otherwise do something with it. Since C++17, you should be using std::optional to achieve this.

- Writing data to a specific memory address. If a function needs to return multiple data, you can have it take in pointers, to which it will write the data to. You’ll only really see this when working with C libraries, since in C++, you should use references for this, if possible.

- Raw arrays. C-style arrays can be treated like they are pointers to the first element of the array. When a raw array is passed to a function, it also decays into a pointer. You should avoid raw arrays unless you have a good reason for using them, and instead use an STL container, like std::vector, std::array, std::unordered_map, or one of the many others.

- Raw strings. C-style strings are just const arrays of characters, so you would typically just store a const pointer to them. You shouldn’t really be using raw strings at all in C++. If you want the C++ equivalent of C-style strings, use std::string_view. If you want strings with more functionality, you can use std::string, at a small cost of slight performance loss compared to std::string_view.

A constructor is a member function that gets called when an instance of the object is instantiated. It is used to bring the object into a valid state.

E.g.

    class Foo final
    {
        public:
            int a{0};
            float b{0.0f};

            Foo() = default;
            Foo(int a, float b) noexcept;
    }; 

    Foo::Foo(int a, float b) noexcept
    : a{a},
    b{b}
    {
        // Maybe some code here...
    }

    int main()
    {
        // Default constructor is called, a and b are 0.
        Foo foo1;
        // Non-default constructor is called, a is 32 and b is 64.0f
        Foo foo2{32, 64.0f};

        return 0;
    }

Member functions (what you called “object functions”) are just functions belonging to a class instance. 

E.g.

    class Foo final
    {
    public:
        // Unrelated, but since both of these functions will end up being one-liners, they’re defined in the class declaration so that they can be marked as “inline”
        int getNum() const noexcept { return num; }
        int setNum(int num) noexcept
        {
            assert(num >= 0 && “Number cannot be negative!”);
            this->num = num;
        }

    private:
        int num{0};
    };

    int main()
    {
        Foo foo;
        foo.setNum(25);
        std::cout << foo.getNum() << ‘\n’;

        return 0;
    }

Hope this helps.

