@Jude M haha I'll try to explain it better.

- Although, for whatever reason, using namespace std is common in teaching material, you should avoid writing it, as it's widely considered to be bad practice. Just prefix everything from the standard library with std::.

e.g.

    std::string_view msg{"Hello world!"};
    std::cout << msg << '\n';

-  If you want to end the line after outputting data to a stream, like std::cout, use '\n' (see my previous example). If you want to end the line and also flush the stream, you can use std::endl. By default, std::cout is buffered, and its output is printed when the buffer is full, or when you insert a newline. If you want it to print right away, you can flush the stream.

e.g.

    std::cout << "Hello world";
    std::cout << std::flush;

std::endl will end the line, and flush the stream. If you don't need it to flush the stream, using std::endl is an unnecessary performance loss. Using '\n' will also make your intention more clear.

- Unless you have a reason to do otherwise, always initialize variables using uniform initialization, with { }.

e.g.

    const int num{25};
    const int *const ptr{&num};
    const std::string str{"Hello World"};
    const std::string &ref{str};

Uniform initialization is safer and the rules for it are simpler. Unlike other forms of initialization, uniform initialization does not allow implicit narrowing. For instance, you can assign a float to a double, but not a double to a float, because double is twice the size of a float, and so a float cannot hold its value. If you for whatever reason needed to do this anyway, you can do so by explicitly casting.

e.g.

    double d{32.0};
    float f1{d}; // Error, implicit narrowing conversion not allowed.
    float f2{static_cast<float>(d)}; // Ok.

    float ff{32.0f};
    double dd{ff}; // Ok.

Another reason to use uniform initialization is because it avoids the most vexing parse. For example, consider this line:

    Foo foo(Foo());

You might think that that line is creating a variable of type Foo, by invoking its copy constructor, copying the passed-in temporary Foo object. In reality, it is actually a function declaration, returning a Foo object, and taking in an unnamed parameter of type Foo. This is how compilers are required to interpret it. However, in this example:

    Foo foo{Foo{}};

It actually creates a variable. You should also know that uniform initialization will always prefer initializer lists, which means that if there's a constructor taking in an std::initializer_list,  uniform initialization will always call that constructor. Consider this:

    std::vector<int> vec{8};

In case you don't know, std::vector has a constructor taking in a size_type count variable. This constructor will allocate enough memory for "count" amount of elements. It may look like that's what that line is doing, but it is actually calling the constructor taking in an std::initializer_list, so it actually creates a vector with one element in it, the int with value of 8. If this is not your intention, you can get around this by using the old-style of initialization, using ( ). 

- Maybe prefer the pre-increment operator, ++x, over the post-increment operator, x++. These two are not identical. The former simply increments the variable, then returns the result. The latter, on the other hand, will create a copy of the old value, increment the variable, then return that old value.

E.g.

    int a{1};
    int b{1};

    std::cout << ++a << '\n';
    std::cout << b++ << '\n';

    Output:
    2
    1

For fundamental types, it doesn't make much difference, if any at all, so it doesn't really matter which one you use. However, if you're incrementing a larger object, using the post-increment operator when the pre-increment operator will do just fine can lead to unnecessary performance loss. It's pretty common practice to always use the pre-increment operator (++x), unless you *need* to get the old value first, in which case you can use the post-increment operator (x++).

Hope this helps.

