Everything inside the standard library is defined inside the std namespace. A namespace just provides a named scope for your symbols. Here’s an example:

    namespace io
    {
       inline void print(std::string_view str) noexcept
        {
            std::cout <<str << “\n”;
        }
    }

    namespace revIo
    {
        void print(std::string str) noexcept
        {
            std::reverse(str.begin(), str.end());
            std::cout << str << “\n”;
        } 
    }

    int main()
    {
        io::print(“Hello”); // Prints the string “Hello.”
        revIo::print(“Hello”); // Prints the string “Hello” in reverse.
        print(“Hello”); // Error, no such function exists.
    } 

What using namespace std does is tell the compiler to treat all symbols defined in the namespace std as if they were defined in the global namespace. This way, you don’t have to prefix everything that’s a part of the standard library with std::. Doing using namespace std is widely considered to be bad practice, so you should probably avoid doing it. However, doing using namespace x is alright when you’re in a smaller scope, such as a function. It could be useful if that function is using just that one library, or if it’s using something from a namespace with a long name, such as std::chrono. If you’re still going to be writing using namespace at a file-wide scope, just remember to *never do using namespace in a header file.* Since the include directive just copies and pastes the contents of the included file, every time you include that file you’ll bring the using namespace statement with you, and this could introduce a heaps of issues.

Also, if you don’t already know, you can also just expose a single symbol into the global namespace like this:

    using std::cout; // Only exposes std::cout.
    std::string in;
