@Wan Khai A function needs to return something if it has a non-void return type. If you do not need the function to return some data, you can just make the return type void. The main function needs to return an exit code. If it returns 0, it means that the program ran fine. If the program ran into an issue, you’d usually return a non-0 value. You can actually omit the return statement from the main function, and the compiler will implicitly add one for you, which will just return 0.

To answer your second question, a function that does have a return statement in it returns some data. For example:

    int add(int a, int b) noexcept
    {
        return a + b;
    }

That function calculates a + b and returns the result. If a function has a non-void return type and doesn’t return anything, it will result in undefined behaviour (if you’re in debug mode, usually the compiler won’t even try to compile it). If the function does have a void return type, there is no need to add a return statement, although you can if you want to return out of the function early. Return statements in void functions just exit out of the function without giving you any data.

E.g.

    void foo() noexcept
    {
        // If condition is true, only this part will be executed.
        if (condition)
        {
            statement1();
            return;
        }

        // This part will only be executed if the condition is not true.
        statement2();
        statement3();
        }

