OP KP Java’s syntax is based on C and C++, but everything else about Java and C++ is very different. What can be considered good Java code, could be very bad C++ code. Java is much simpler, and is used for different tasks than C++. C++ is a much more complicated language as it offers better performance and more control.

As a very very simple example, this is how you create a new object in Java:

Foo foo = new Foo();

You can do the same thing in C++ like this:

Foo *foo = new Foo{};

But unless you for some reason need to allocate the object on the free-store, this is a bad idea, as allocating it on the stack would probably be faster.

Foo foo;

In Java, that would actually create a null pointer, but in C++, it creates a new object on the stack. If you did need to allocate it on the free-store, doing so with new is probably a bad idea, as you would have to manually manage the memory, and it can sometimes not be exception safe. Instead, you’d need to do it the RAII way.

// Unique pointer is used here, but you can also use a different smart pointer, like shared_ptr if you need shared ownership.
std::unique_ptr<Foo> foo{std::make_unique<Foo>()};

You may also have noticed that instead of using (), I used { }. That is because those two initialize variables a bit differently. You can use () just like you can in Java:

Foo *foo = new Foo();

But in C++, you should always prefer to initialize variables with { }. The rules for it are simpler, less ambiguous, and safer than other forms of initialization.

As you can see, even something simple like creating a new object is very different between these two languages. 

If you want another example, here’s how you cast in Java:

    float f = 32.0f;
    System.out.println((int)f);

But in C++, although you can still use the C-style cast, it is recommended that you actually specify what type of cast you want. For this example, you’d use static_cast:

    float f = 32.0f;
     std::cout << static_cast<int>(f);

In C++, there’s static_cast, dynamic_cast, reinterpret_cast, c-style cast, and function-style casts. 

I hope this helps you understand how these two languages are completely different, apart from they’re similar syntax.

