CodeBlocks and CLion are not code editors, they’re IDEs.

The correct way to do it would be to prefix everything from the standard library with std, like you’re doing. The reason you have to do this, is because everything in the standard library is defined in the std namespace. Namespaces provide a scope to all the identifiers. They are used to prevent name collisions, and keep code more organized. If you don’t want to prefix all the standard library code with std, you can use the using keyword. You can make the compiler treat all identifiers within the specified namespace by doing using namespace your_namespace;

E.g.

using namespace std;
string str{“Hello World”};
cout << str << “\n”;

However, this is often considered bad practice. You should only use using namespace when you are in a limited scope, such as a function, and are using something from a namespace with a long name.

You can also do something like this:

using std::string;
string a{“Hello”};
string b{“Word”};
std::cout << a << “ “ << b << “\n”;

This is better than doing using namespace, but in this case it’s still unnecessary since the standard namespace name is very short, so it’s not that difficult to type the full name out.

Also, you shouldn’t use the assignment operator to initialize objects. You should initialize everything with {}.

E.g.

std::chrono::milliseconds ms{1500};

However, I still like to use the assignment operator to initialize only fundamental types, references, and pointers.

